Perfect ðŸš€ Here are the main notes for your question:

ðŸ”¹ Next.js API Routes & CRUD Notes
1. What are API Routes in Next.js?

Next.js lets you create backend APIs inside the same project (no need for separate Express server).

You create files inside /pages/api/ â†’ each file becomes an API endpoint.

Runs only on the server-side (never exposed to client).

2. How Next.js Handles API Routes?

Any file inside /pages/api/ is treated as an API endpoint.

Export a default function (req, res) â†’ it handles the request.

Supports all HTTP methods: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE.

3. Simple CRUD API Example
ðŸ“‚ Folder structure:
pages/
 â””â”€â”€ api/
      â””â”€â”€ users.js

users.js
let users = [];

export default function handler(req, res) {
  if (req.method === "GET") {
    res.status(200).json(users); // Read
  } 
  else if (req.method === "POST") {
    const newUser = req.body;
    users.push(newUser); // Create
    res.status(201).json(newUser);
  } 
  else if (req.method === "PUT") {
    const { id, name } = req.body;
    users = users.map(u => (u.id === id ? { ...u, name } : u)); // Update
    res.status(200).json({ message: "User updated" });
  } 
  else if (req.method === "DELETE") {
    const { id } = req.body;
    users = users.filter(u => u.id !== id); // Delete
    res.status(200).json({ message: "User deleted" });
  } 
  else {
    res.setHeader("Allow", ["GET", "POST", "PUT", "DELETE"]);
    res.status(405).end(`Method ${req.method} Not Allowed`);
  }
}

4. Key Points to Remember

âœ… API routes run only on server â†’ safe for secrets.
âœ… Great for small projects, form submissions, authentication, etc.
âœ… For large apps, you might still use Express/Nest.js with Next.js.
âœ… req.body requires middleware like body-parser or Next.js built-in support for JSON.
